Maintainer: Ottavia M. Epifania <ottavia.epifania@unitn.it>
Description: Implement different Item Response Theory (IRT) based procedures for the development 
        of static short test forms (STFs) from a test. Different procedures are considered (Epifania, Anselmi & Robusto, 2022 <doi:10.1007/978-3-031-27781-8_7> and Epifania & Finos, 2025 <doi:>).
        The procedures differ according to: (i) how the most informative items are selected for the inclusion in the STF, and (ii) how the information is considered and defined for the item inclusion in the STF. Concering the former point, the items are selected either by considering their item information functions without any reference to any specific latent trait level (benchmark procedure) or by considering their information 
        with respect to specific latent trait levels, denoted as theta targets (theta target procedure). Concerning the latter point, the theta target procedure differes from the item selection procedure (item selection algorithm, ISA) in how the target
        information is defined. Specifically, instead of defining the targets as discrete latent trait levels for which the information needs to be maximized (theta-target procedure), ISA works by definining a test information function target that needs to be approximated as much as possible 
        with the items inlcuded in the STF. As such, the distance between the information function target and that of the STF has to be minimized. A key consequence of this difference is that since the information for each theta target has to be maximized, the number of defined theta targets
        also defines the number of items in the STF. Differently, once the distance from the test information target is minimized, ISA stops, regardless of the number of items included up to that point.
        For further details on the procedure, please refer to Epifania, Anselmi & Robusto (2022) <doi:10.1007/978-3-031-27781-8_7> and Epifania and Finos (2025) <doi:>.
